4 SYNOPSIS:
5 This bill creates the Medical Research Supply
6 Assurance and Trade Resilience Act to enhance health
7 care and biotechnology sectors by safeguarding critical
8 research and medical supply chains against global trade
9 disruptions through strategic stockpiling, domestic
10 incentives, and biomedical trade facilitation programs.
11 This bill will also create the Medical Research
12 Supply Assurance and Trade Resilience Program Fund.
13
14
15 A BILL
16 TO BE ENTITLED
17 AN ACT
18
19 Relating to global trade disruptions to medical or
20 research materials; to establish the Essential Medical Supply
21 Resilience Grant Program; to require the Alabama Department of
22 Public Health to research trade risks; to establish a reserve
23 of essential research and clinical supplies within the Alabama
24 Department of Public Health; and to establish the Medical
25 Supply Chain Vulnerability Advisory Board.
26 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
27 Section 1. This act shall be known as the Medical
28 Research Supply Assurance and Trade Resilience Act.
Page 1

Research Supply Assurance and Trade Resilience Act.
HB547 INTRODUCED
29 Section 2. As used in this act, unless otherwise
30 specified or unless the context requires otherwise, the
31 following terms will have the following meanings:
32 (1) DEPARTMENT. The Alabama Department of Public
33 Health.
34 (2) ELIGIBLE INSTITUTION. Any of the following
35 institutions:
36 a. A hospital meeting the definition found in Section
37 22-21-20(1), Code of Alabama 1975.
38 b. A research university operating within the state.
39 c. A biotechnology company operating within the state.
40 d. A health care facility meeting the definition found
41 in Section 22-21-260(6), Code of Alabama 1975.
42 (3) TRADE DISRUPTION. Any period in which the average
43 tariff on medical or research materials is over five percent.
44 Section 3. (a) The department shall establish the
45 Essential Medical Supply Resilience Grant Program.
46 (b) The department may establish priorities,
47 guidelines, standards, and processes by which grants may be
48 awarded.
49 (c) Grants may be awarded to eligible institutions
50 experiencing increased costs, delays, or shortages related to
51 global trade instability.
52 (d) The department shall require interested eligible
53 institutions to complete applications on forms issued by the
54 department that will substantiate the eligible institution's
55 need for the grant.
56 (e) Funds may be used for substitute sourcing,
Page 2

(e) Funds may be used for substitute sourcing,
HB547 INTRODUCED
57 stockpiling, domestic supplier development, or related
58 mitigation strategies.
59 Section 4. (a) The department shall support efforts to:
60 (1) Identify critical imported biomedical inputs
61 subject to trade risks;
62 (2) Facilitate research into domestic or tariff-neutral
63 substitutes; and
64 (3) Promote partnerships with in-state manufacturers to
65 produce essential inputs.
66 (b) Grants under the Essential Medical Supply
67 Resilience Grant Program and technical assistance to eligible
68 institutions shall be prioritized for those institutions
69 facing the highest exposure to trade disruptions.
70 Section 5. (a) The department shall create and maintain
71 a strategic reserve of essential research and clinical
72 supplies.
73 (b) The reserve shall include reagents, personal
74 protective equipment, diagnostic kits, and lab consumables.
75 (c) Eligible institutions may request access to the
76 reserve during periods of documented international trade
77 disruption.
78 Section 6. (a) The department shall provide support to
79 eligible institutions in:
80 (1) Navigating customs clearance and import licensing;
81 (2) Understanding international health material
82 regulations; and
83 (3) Mitigating impacts of export controls or
84 retaliatory tariffs on biomedical goods.
Page 3

retaliatory tariffs on biomedical goods.
